<div id="review_291580162" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/291580162" />
    <a title="Jolanda" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4455395-jolanda"><img alt="Jolanda" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1316021792p2/4455395.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/291580162?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jolanda" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jolanda" href="/user/show/4455395-jolanda">Jolanda</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer291580162&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer291580162" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16444411298224255978">Am I Blue? Is a collection of short stories written by terrific authors and collected by Marion Dane Bauer, all to do with coming out or addressing homosexuality especially in the family. Ranging from amusing results in the face of torment like the first and titular work Am I Blue is about a tormented boy being able to see everybody who is gay/lesbian or has experimented in homosexuality when they turn blue; including the bully. In this first story he has a fairy godfather who fulfills the “swis</span>
  <span id="freeText16444411298224255978" style="display:none">Am I Blue? Is a collection of short stories written by terrific authors and collected by Marion Dane Bauer, all to do with coming out or addressing homosexuality especially in the family. Ranging from amusing results in the face of torment like the first and titular work Am I Blue is about a tormented boy being able to see everybody who is gay/lesbian or has experimented in homosexuality when they turn blue; including the bully. In this first story he has a fairy godfather who fulfills the “swishy” stereotypical gay role.<br />To the sad and realistic Winnie and Tommy, In the Tunnels, Parent’s Night and Holding. Winnie and Tommy are high schoolers grappling with sexuality and identity in unfortunate family situations. While In the Tunnels is based in Cu Chi as if this desperate couple were surviving tunnel warfare during the Vietnam War as well as trying to keep their secret. Parent’s Night is slightly more cheerful. It begins with secrecy then the Gay-Straight-Bisexual-Alliance at Karen’s school needs students to man their booth for the school parent’s night and Karen and her girlfriend Roxy are chosen. When Karen confronts her social worker mother for her ill-informed bordering on hypocritical fear of AIDS and abruptly comes out she almost loses her family; until a belated birthday present arrives. Holding presents a different and equally special perspective on homosexuality in the family; in this case Willie goes to comfort his father at the death of his longtime partner Chris. The two men had been a part of Willies life for a long time, his mother and Chris even liked each other. In the end Willie comes clean to his best friend about Chris’ gender, each step in Willie’s story is marked by comforting holding.<br />The most different of all the short stories in Am I Blue is Jane Yolen’s contribution. A combination of supernatural or magical elements and different story telling styles Blood Sisters is also a prequel to several of her longer works.<br />This collection is unusual and a bit revolutionary in its contents to learn about the progression of gay and lesbian themes in literature there is a brief introduction, and each story is accompanied by a short author biography. Though I described only a fraction of this work I suggest it as a great anthology for any “young people in their search for themselves.” (Bauer 1994) <br />Since before its publication the concept has been under fire and since 1994 Am I Blue has been on one challenged list or another. I found it in Hit list for young adults frequently challenged books 2; which is where I would begin my search for another book like this, since it has detailed descriptions of why they are under fire. In addition to challenges Am I Blue received the Kerlan Award in 1996. (Presented by the Kerlan friends and the Children’s Literature Research Collection of Minnesota Library)</span>
  <a data-text-id="16444411298224255978" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

