<div id="review_834137606" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/834137606" />
    <a title="Kyle Moore" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17415635-kyle-moore"><img alt="Kyle Moore" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360803235p2/17415635.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/834137606?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kyle Moore" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kyle Moore" href="/user/show/17415635-kyle-moore">Kyle Moore</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer834137606" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12001698408086742408">Having wanted to read so badly (as I hadn&apos;t in weeks), I found this in my school library, and thought, &quot;well, why not.&quot; It is an LGBT anthology, and I am bisexual, so it might be something that I enjoy.<br/><br/>And I certainly enjoyed it.<br/><br/>For one, I loved how realistic of it all. I could relate to all the characters, and especially the one from &quot;Three Mondays in July&quot;. I could relate because in a similar fashion, I had learned that I was into my own gender, and I could relate to how he was scared to tell </span>
  <span id="freeText12001698408086742408" style="display:none">Having wanted to read so badly (as I hadn't in weeks), I found this in my school library, and thought, "well, why not." It is an LGBT anthology, and I am bisexual, so it might be something that I enjoy.<br /><br />And I certainly enjoyed it.<br /><br />For one, I loved how realistic of it all. I could relate to all the characters, and especially the one from "Three Mondays in July". I could relate because in a similar fashion, I had learned that I was into my own gender, and I could relate to how he was scared to tell anyone else anything that he had felt.<br /><br />Another thing I loved, was that none of them were cliche, at all. None of them were the cliche erotic mess with their parents throwing them out and what not. Yes, I know they were short stories and all and there isn't enough time to put that kind of stuff into the story. But most didn't even imply anything sexual. It was certainly refreshing.<br /><br />My favorite stories out of all of them were "The Honorary Shepherds" and "Parent's Night". I love these stories because they were one, relatable, and because of the way they were written. I loved "The Honorary Shepherds" for both, as the author Gregory Maguire made it funny from the beginning, or at least it had the kind of sarcasm that I love in stories. I also enjoyed how it was written mostly in second person, you rarely if ever see that in stories. I loved "Parent's Night", because when I came out, something similar happen to me, without the Gay Alliance and the girlfriend and all. <br /><br />At this point, I bet you are wondering why I gave this story four out of five stars rather than five out of five. There is only one complaint that I have, and it is about the story "Blood Sister" by Jane Yolen. It made no sense to me, in how it went from myth to story and the religion made no sense and the world in general made no sense to me either. It was the only story in the whole anthology that I didn't like.<br /><br />But in the end, the stories were mostly amazing, and it is something that I really related to. I would certainly recommend this book to almost anyone, as it really lets you into the world of LGBT people, and people who know LGBT people.<br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12001698408086742408" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


